As Brad wrote to Dr. Math
On 09/22/2004 at 09:23:16 (Eastern Time),
>[Question]
>This seems like it should be really simple, but I just don't get it. 
>I need to simplify this equation for area of a flat circular ring, 
>but I'm not sure where to start. x is the inner ring radius, x + 1/y 
>is the outer radius:
>
>A = [pi * (x + 1/y) * (x + 1/y)] - (pi * x * x)
>
>
>
>[Difficulty]
>The examples I have seen on your site make me think I should start by 
>changing x + 1/y to (xy + 1)/y, but I just seem to end up with more 
>complex equations as I go, not simpler ones. I also tried using FOIL 
>on the (x + 1/y) pair, but not sure if that is the way to go either. 
>
>[Thoughts]
>I really want to "get" this. please help. I was never good at algebra 
>in school, but I like it when I can understand some small piece of it.
>

Hello Brad,

Well,

(x+1/y)*(x+1/y) = x^2+2x/y+1/y^2

and so

pi*(x+1/y)*(x+1/y) - pi*x^2 = pi*(2x/y+1/y^2)

=pi*(2x*y+1)/y^2


